Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
(Case called at 2:00 PM) Defendant Seth J. Dux in court.  Attorney Brian A Braziel in court for Seth J. Dux.  Attorney Trenton John Piltz in court for State of Wisconsin. 
State in compliance with victim notification requirements. Defense indicates there is an agreement and recites the joint sentence recommendation. Defendant is advised of charges, maximum penalties, elements of the crime(s) and constitutional rights. Defendant pleads Guilty to Count 2- Operating Firearm While Intoxicated and Count 3- Domestic Disorderly Conduct as part of 12 month Deferred Acceptance of a Guilty Plea Agreement. Court approves Deferred Acceptance of a Guilty Plea Agreement and withholds finding of guilt for Counts 2 and 3. 
State moves to dismiss Count 1- 2nd Degree Recklessly Endangering Safety as Domestic. Court orders Count 2 is dismissed on prosecutor's motion.
Deferred prosecution agreement hearing scheduled for July 31, 2023 at 09:30 am.

Defendant waives reading of Information and enters Not Guilty pleas- Received by the Court. Court orders 20 days for motions (can be extended for Good Cause). Defense advises there is a DAGP offer that may resolve the case. Court advises defendant to be in touch with the DAGP coordinator. 
A status conference (possible plea) is scheduled for 7/28/2022 at 2:00 PM (in person).
